INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '76883253-fc5d-4858-ba98-f472da6da549',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Redis Idempotency — Designing Consumers to Safely Handle Duplicate Messages$escape$,
  $escape$Redis Streams and List-based queues can deliver duplicates — network retries, consumer crashes mid-ACK, or XAUTOCLAIM reassignments all cause reprocessing. The fix: gate every consumer on a Redis SET-based idempotency key before doing work.

Use SETNX (or SET ... NX EX) with a TTL tied to your message retention window. When a consumer picks up a message, it atomically attempts to claim the message ID as a key. If the key already exists, the message was already processed — skip it and ACK. If not, process and then ACK with XACK.

For Streams specifically, use the message ID (e.g. 1700000000000-0) as the idempotency key — it's globally unique per stream. For LPOP/RPOP queues where you control message shape, embed a UUID in the payload and use that.

Keep TTLs at least 2× your consumer SLA. Use a Lua script to atomically check-and-set + process if you need the entire operation to be atomic. Avoid using INCR counters as idempotency guards — they don't survive TTL expiry correctly under retry storms.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Lua script: atomic idempotency check + claim
local key = 'idempotent:' .. ARGV[1]  -- ARGV[1] = message ID
local ttl = tonumber(ARGV[2])          -- e.g. 86400 seconds

local result = redis.call('SET', key, '1', 'NX', 'EX', ttl)
if result then
  return 1  -- claimed: safe to process
else
  return 0  -- duplicate: skip and ACK
end$escape$,
  $escape$lua$escape$,
